<div class=3D"pr-0 pr-lg-5">
<p>If the minute value of the ending time is smaller than the minute value =
of the starting time, you'll need to "borrow" an hour from the hour value o=
f the ending time. If the ending hour is a smaller value than the starting =
hour, the value of the difference will be a negative number. In this case, =
you should add 24 hours to the result.</p>
<p>So, in our example, since subtracting minutes from the ending time yield=
ed a negative number (-15), we should add 60 to the minutes, then adjust th=
e hours. So, instead of -15, we=E2=80=99ll have 45, and instead of 500, we=
=E2=80=99ll have 400.</p>
<p>First, add the minutes to the hours. From there, you can convert the for=
mat from military time to standard hours and minutes or to decimal format. =
In our example, the result is 445, which is 4 hours and 45 minutes, or 4.75=
 hours.</p>
